# Agent 1B — Roadmap Ingestion
 
Handles 6 different roadmap source types. Regardless of source, produces
the same Normalised Roadmap Package that all downstream agents consume.
 
**Critical discipline:** The roadmap is the source of truth for what the team
*committed* to. The audit measures drift from this commitment. If no roadmap
exists, the audit can still run — but strategic coherence analysis (Agent 5)
will be limited to OKR alignment rather than roadmap drift.
 
---
 
## Source Type Handling
 
### Aha! (Enterprise Structured)
 
If Aha! MCP connected (or if PM provides Aha! export):
 
Extract per initiative/feature:
```
- Initiative name + description
- Features under each initiative
- Release/quarter target
- Priority (MoSCoW or custom scale)
- Status (Under Consideration / Planned / In Development / Shipped)
- OKR or goal link (Aha! has native goal linking)
- Owner
- % complete (if tracked)
```
 
Map Aha! hierarchy to normalised format:
```
Aha! Goal      → Strategic Objective (= OKR level)
Aha! Initiative → Theme / Epic
Aha! Feature   → Feature commitment
Aha! Release   → Quarter/Sprint target
```
 
### Confluence Tables / Pages
 
Read the Confluence page. Identify roadmap structure (usually one of):
- A table with columns: Feature | Quarter | Priority | Status | Owner
- A page with H2 headings per quarter, bullet features underneath
- A prioritised backlog section in a spec or strategy doc
 
Extraction approach:
```
For tables: parse columns, map to normalised fields (flexible — column names vary)
For prose: extract any item that has: a feature name + a time indicator
           (Q1/Q2/H1/Sprint N/January) + a priority signal (P1/Critical/Must-have)
```
 
If Confluence MCP connected: fetch by URL or search for "roadmap" in the space.
If not: ask PM to paste the roadmap table or copy the relevant page content.
 
### Excel / Google Sheets
 
Most fintech PMs who roadmap in Excel use one of two patterns:
- **Gantt-style:** Rows = features, Columns = weeks/months/quarters (shaded = in scope)
- **Backlog-style:** Rows = features, Columns = Name | Quarter | Priority | Status | OKR
 
For Google Sheets: if MCP connected, fetch by URL.
For Excel: accept file upload or CSV export.
 
**Flexible column detection** — do NOT require exact column names. Detect by:
```
Feature/item column:   first text column with long values (feature names)
Time column:           column with Q1/Q2/Q3/Q4 or month names or sprint numbers
Priority column:       column with values like P1/P2/High/Medium/Critical/MoSCoW
Status column:         values like Done/In Progress/Planned/Backlog/Shipped
OKR/Goal column:       column referencing goals, OKRs, or strategic themes
```
 
When columns are ambiguous, show PM the detected mapping and ask for confirmation
before running analysis.
 
### Notion Databases
 
If Notion MCP connected: fetch the roadmap database by URL.
 
Standard Notion roadmap properties to look for:
```
Name (title), Status (select), Quarter (select or date), 
Priority (select), Team/Owner (person), OKR (relation or text),
Sprint (number or select), Feature type (select)
```
 
If properties use non-standard names (PMs customise heavily):
detect by property type and value patterns, same as Excel above.
 
### Linear Roadmap View
 
Linear's roadmap is project-based. Extract:
```
Projects (= roadmap themes/initiatives)
  → Milestones within each project (= quarterly targets)
  → Status of each milestone
  → Issues assigned to each milestone (= committed features)
```
 
If Linear MCP connected: auto-fetch.
If not: ask PM to export or screenshot + describe the roadmap.
 
### Productboard
 
Productboard has a feature prioritisation and roadmap view. Extract:
```
Features in "Now" / "Next" / "Later" lanes (or custom lanes)
Features linked to objectives
Prioritisation scores (if PM has set them)
Release dates/quarters
```
 
If Productboard is not MCP-connected: ask PM to export CSV from Productboard
(Features → Export to CSV) or paste the current roadmap view.
 
### Paste / Upload (Tool-Agnostic Primary)
 
Accept any format:
- Prose description of the roadmap ("This quarter we planned to ship X, Y, Z")
- Numbered or bulleted list of features with priorities
- Copy-paste from any tool
- Screenshot description (PM describes what's in the screenshot)
 
From paste: extract every item that has:
- A name (what the feature/item is)
- A time target (when it was planned)
- At minimum implied priority (if mentioned)
 
Flag: paste-sourced roadmaps will have lower confidence — the audit will note
where roadmap interpretation required inference.
 
---
 
## Normalised Roadmap Package
 
Output structure (identical regardless of source):
 
```
ROADMAP PACKAGE
════════════════
Source:      [Aha! / Confluence / Excel / Notion / Linear / Productboard / Paste]
Period:      [Quarter / Sprint / Date range]
Extracted:   [N] roadmap commitments
Confidence:  [HIGH — structured tool / MEDIUM — table/doc / LOW — prose/paste]
 
COMMITTED FEATURES (for this audit period):
[For each item:]
 
  FEATURE: [Name]
  ───────────────
  Theme/Initiative:  [parent epic or theme, or "standalone"]
  Planned period:    [Q1 / Sprint N / Month]
  Priority:          [P1/Critical/Must-have/High — or normalised to H/M/L]
  OKR link:          [explicit link / inferred from description / none]
  Owner:             [team or person]
  Status at audit:   [Shipped / In progress / Not started / Deprioritised]
  Jira epic link:    [if cross-referenceable to sprint data]
 
FEATURES PLANNED BUT NOT IN SPRINT DATA:
[Items on roadmap that don't appear in any sprint ticket — potential drift]
 
FEATURES IN SPRINT DATA BUT NOT ON ROADMAP:
[Items delivered that weren't committed to — emergent or reactive work]
 
ROADMAP HEALTH SUMMARY:
  Total commitments for period:   [N]
  Matched to sprint deliveries:   [N] ([X%])
  On roadmap, not delivered:      [N] ([X%])
  Delivered, not on roadmap:      [N] ([X%])
  Roadmap fidelity score:         [X%] — [HIGH >80% / MEDIUM 50-80% / LOW <50%]
```
 
---
 
## When There Is No Roadmap
 
If the PM has no roadmap:
 
```
Flag clearly: "No roadmap provided. Strategic coherence analysis (Agent 5)
will be based on OKR alignment only — we can assess whether work linked to
stated objectives, but cannot measure drift from explicit commitments."
 
Proceed with: Agents 1A, 1C, 1D, 2, 3, 4, 6, 7 — all can run without roadmap
Skip: Agent 5 roadmap drift section (replace with OKR-alignment-only analysis)
```
 
No roadmap is itself an audit finding. Surface it in Agent 7 (Uncomfortable Truths)
if the team claims to have strategic direction but cannot produce a roadmap.